{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488415"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"435"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/435"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.12,0.04,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94452"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/435"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77491"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"398"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31300"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94452"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-day history of colicky abdominal pain and distension. This morning she felt nauseated and started vomiting. Her bowels last opened two days ago. She has a medical history of an appendicectomy and thyroidectomy. She takes no regular medications. She has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks four to five alcoholic drinks per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her abdomen is distended, but soft. High pitched bowel sounds can be heard. There is a 3 cm diameter tender swelling in the right groin, situated immediately below the inguinal ligament. Digital examination reveals an empty rectum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following features would suggest the most urgent need for surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The recent onset of vomiting","The empty rectum","The high-pitched bowel sounds","The time duration of her current problem","The tender swelling"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has small bowel obstruction - almost certainly due to a strangulated femoral hernia. Certainly, the commonest cause of intestinal obstruction in developed countries tends to be a small bowel obstruction secondary to adhesions - and this patient has a common cause of adhesion formation, namely a previous appendicectomy. However, she has a \u003Cstrong\u003Etender swelling\u003C/strong\u003E in the groin, and one situated below the inguinal ligament is a femoral hernia. The finding that it is tender is a strong indication that the hernia is strangulated - ie its contents have become ischaemic. Thus the patient requires urgent surgery, not so much to deal with the obstruction, but more to prevent to contents of the hernia (a segment of small bowel) from becoming gangrenous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erecent onset of vomiting\u003C/strong\u003E is certainly consistent with an underlying problem of intestinal obstruction. However this symptom in itself does not warrant any urgent intervention and will usually resolve rapidly once the cause of the obstruction has been resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eempty rectum\u003C/strong\u003E could be consistent with a diagnosis of large bowel obstruction, but this observation only points towards a diagnosis, rather than hastening any decisions for active intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh pitched bowel sounds\u003C/strong\u003E are a common finding in cases of intestinal obstruction, but in themselves, are not an indication for any urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECertainly the longer the duration of a patient\u0027s symptoms, the more the likelihood that some sort of active intervention will be required to deal with the underlying problem. However, a two day \u003Cstrong\u003Eduration of symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E in this case, by themselves is not an indication for urgent surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tenderness on palpation of hernia suggests ischaemia of the contents."],"references":["Catena F, De Simone B, Coccolini F, Di Saverio S, Sartelli M, Ansaloni L. Bowel obstruction: a narrative review for all physicians. World J Emerg Surg. 2019;14:20. . Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6489175/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77491"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"435"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77491"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T09:15:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T09:15:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"435"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94452"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"htt